  "footnotes": [
    "Punt: An ancient trading partner of Egypt mentioned in records from c.2500 BCE; traded incense, ebony, gold, and exotic animals; its exact location is debated but the Somali coast and Djibouti area are leading candidates.",
    "Zeila (Zayla): A key Red Sea port city at modern Djibouti/Somaliland border; one of the oldest cities in Africa; served as the capital of the Ifat and Adal Sultanates and a major terminus for Ethiopian trade.",
    "Ajuran Sultanate (c.1300–1700): A powerful Somali sultanate centred in the Jubba and Shabelle river valleys; known for its sophisticated hydraulic engineering (wells and reservoirs) and resistance to Portuguese and Oromo encroachments.",
    "Dervish State (1895–1920): Led by Mohammed Abdullah Hassan (called 'Mad Mullah' by the British); fought a 20-year guerrilla war against British, Italian, and Ethiopian forces; ended when the British used air power (first use in Africa) to bomb his fort.",
    "Republic of Somaliland (1991–): Declared independence from Somalia after the collapse of the Barre regime; maintains de facto independence with its own government, currency, and military; unrecognised by any UN member state but considered stable.",
    "Somali civil war (1991–): Collapse of Siad Barre's government led to clan-based civil war; the warlord period (1991–2006), Islamic Courts Union (2006), Ethiopian intervention (2006–2009), Al-Shabaab insurgency (2009–present).",
    "Al-Shabaab: Somali Islamist group affiliated with Al-Qaeda; controls rural areas of southern and central Somalia; carries out attacks across the region including Kenya and Ethiopia."
  ]
